:R-HSA-418597  a            owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0008150 ;
        rdfs:comment        "The heterotrimeric G protein G alpha (z), is a member of the G (i) family. Unlike other G alpha (i) family members it lacks an ADP ribosylation site cysteine four residues from the carboxyl terminus and is thus pertussis toxin-insensitive. It inhibits adenylyl cyclase types I, V and VI (Wong Y H et al. 1992). G alpha (z) interacts with the Rap1 GTPase activating protein (Rap1GAP) to attenuate Rap1 signaling. Like all G-proteins G alpha (z) has an intrinsic GTPase activity, but this activity tends to be lower for the pertussis toxin insensitive G-proteins, most strikingly so for G alpha (z), whose kcat value for GTP hydrolysis is 200-fold lower than those of G alpha (s) or G alpha (i) (Grazziano et al. 1989). G alpha (z) knockout mice have disrupted platelet aggregation at physiological concentrations of epinephrine and responses to several neuroactive drugs are altered (Yang et al. 2000). Regulator of G-protein Signalling (RGS) proteins can regulate the activity of G alpha (z) (Soundararajan M et al. 2008)." ;
        rdfs:label          "G alpha (z) signalling events" ;
        dc:contributor      "Authored: Jupe, S, 2009-04-24 08:15:10" , "Reviewed: Akkerman, JW, 2009-06-03" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Edited: Jupe, S, 2009-09-09" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-418597" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-388396/R-HSA-388396> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

